'''Rapporteur''' (derived from French) is used in international and European legal and political contexts to refer to a person appointed by a deliberative body to investigate an issue or a situation, and report back to that body.

For example, [[Dick Marty]] was appointed ''rapporteur'' by the [[Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe]] to investigate the allegations of [[extraordinary rendition]] by the [[CIA]], and [[Christopher Newbury]] was appointed as the ''rapporteur'' of the [[CLRAE|Congress of the Council of Europe]] on the proposed revision of the [[European Charter of Local Self-Government]].

